abstract:
This paper considers the unlabeled sparse recovery under multiple measurements, i.e., ${\mathbf{Y}} = {\mathbf{\Pi}}^{
atural} {\mathbf{X}} {\mathbf{B}}^{
atural} + {\mathbf{W}}$, where ${\mathbf{Y}} \in \mathbb{R}^{n	imes m}, {\mathbf{\Pi}}^{
atural}\in \mathbb{R}^{n	imes n}, {\mathbf{X}} \in \mathbb{R}^{n	imes p}, {\mathbf{B}} ^{
atural}\in \mathbb{R}^{p	imes m}, {\mathbf{W}}\in \mathbb{R}^{n	imes m}$ represents the observations, missing (or incomplete) correspondence information, sensing matrix, sparse signals, and additive sensing noise, respectively. Different from the previous works on multiple measurements ($m > 1$) which all focus on the sufficient samples regime, namely, $n > p$, we consider a sparse matrix $\mathbf{B}^{
atural}$ and investigate the insufficient samples regime (i.e., $n \ll p$) for the first time. To begin with, we establish the lower bound on the sample number and
